1. Environment Variables

Sometimes we use the same value many times.

Example:

Instead of writing:

sh 'mvn clean package'

everywhere, we can store values in variables.

Example:

pipeline {

    agent any

    environment {

        APP_NAME = "employee-webapp"

        ENV = "DEV"

    }

    stages {

        stage('Info') {

            steps {

                echo "Application : ${APP_NAME}"

                echo "Environment : ${ENV}"

            }

        }

    }

}
Output
Application : employee-webapp

Environment : DEV
Why Environment Variables?

Suppose tomorrow your application name changes.

Without variables:

employee-webapp

employee-webapp

employee-webapp

employee-webapp

Need to change everywhere.

With variables:

APP_NAME="employee-webapp"

Change only one line.

2. Build Parameters

Sometimes users want to choose something before starting the build.

Example:

Deploy to:

DEV

QA

UAT

PROD

Instead of creating four jobs, we use Parameters.

Example:

pipeline {

    agent any

    parameters {

        choice(
            name: 'ENVIRONMENT',
            choices: ['DEV','QA','UAT'],
            description: 'Select Environment'
        )

    }

    stages {

        stage('Deploy') {

            steps {

                echo "Deploying to ${params.ENVIRONMENT}"

            }

        }

    }

}

Before running the build,

Jenkins asks:

Select Environment

DEV

QA

UAT
Real Company Example

Developer clicks

Build with Parameters

Chooses

QA

Pipeline deploys only to QA.

3. Post Actions

What happens after the build finishes?

Jenkins supports:

always

success

failure

Example:

pipeline {

    agent any

    stages {

        stage('Build') {

            steps {

                echo "Building..."

            }

        }

    }

    post {

        always {

            echo "Pipeline Finished"

        }

        success {

            echo "Build Successful"

        }

        failure {

            echo "Build Failed"

        }

    }

}
If Build Success

Output

Building...

Build Successful

Pipeline Finished
If Build Failed

Output

Build Failed

Pipeline Finished
Why Post Actions?

Real companies use them for:

Email Notifications
Slack Notifications
Teams Notifications
Cleanup
Archive Logs

Example:

Build Failed

↓

Email Team

↓

Create Incident

↓

Notify Slack
4. Complete Pipeline Example
pipeline {

    agent any

    environment {

        APP_NAME = "employee-webapp"

    }

    stages {

        stage('Checkout') {

            steps {

                echo "Downloading Code"

            }

        }

        stage('Build') {

            steps {

                sh 'mvn clean package'

            }

        }

        stage('Deploy') {

            steps {

                echo "Deploying ${APP_NAME}"

            }

        }

    }

    post {

        success {

            echo "Deployment Successful"

        }

        failure {

            echo "Deployment Failed"

        }

        always {

            echo "Pipeline Finished"

        }

    }

}
